    <p>
        <span id="en" class="lang-dependant">
            I have always been curious. I guess the best thing I do was learning.
            <br /><br />
            When I was at primary school I founded a student group of science
            where learning and sharing knowledge about the astronomy, environment, biology and physics.
            <br /><br />
            In the same era, I have met with the marine vessels, from ancient sailing vessels to modern naval crafts.
            That was the big mystery which would take my attention though my whole life.
            <br /><br />
            <b>2014 - Naval Architecture</b>
            <br /><br />
            Well, before any progress I should say that Naval Architecture was my sole choice and dream of my adolescent ages.
            I was overwhelmed by the mystery of floatation and sailing. Passionate to learn principles of fluent dynamics and ship stability.
            I had created a solid understanding in the domain.
            <br /><br />
            I started to design and built my own sailing boat when I started my Bachelor's degree program .
            <br /><br />
            I launched it in 2 years and sailed with it in a summer session.
            When I graduated I become design engineer in the yacht industry.
            <br /><br />
            After 3 years of service I joined the Ministry of Transport and İnfrastructure as a Maritime Expert.
            Worked in development of ship design and construction regulations.
            I had also been assigned as an advisor member of Turkish delegation in the International Maritime Organization (IMO) London headquarters for SDC and MSC committee meetings.
            <br /><br />
            <b>2019-2022 - Transition to Software Development</b>
            <br /><br />
            As an engineer, I learnt to code before graduating, and have used these skills throughout my career in naval architecture.
            I created Excel spreadsheet scripts for analysing design solutions and decision-making processes.
            <br /><br />
            Before 2019, I created a turn-based game in Excel using VBA. It was great fun developing the primitive algorithms.
            <br /><br />
            I was captivated by software development the moment I encountered Arduino and Processing 3, a Java-based visual programming language.
            I had bought an Arduino kit for my little brother, who was at high school at the time.
            While working on a radar project with the kit, I was amazed to realise how accessible it was to create such visual applications.
            <br /><br />
            I was utterly enthralled. I put the Arduino aside and started coding in Processing 3. The more time I spent using it, the more I was drawn in by the software.
            In 2018, I remember coding a mobile game on my phone while flying to Azerbaijan to propose to my future wife. 
            It was this passion that led me to study computer science and software engineering principles in my spare time while developing a 2D isometric game engine.
            <br /><br />
            My new passion had given me new skills and a new mindset. I've always had a strong desire to create and innovate.
            As well as my regular job, I have always taken responsibility for improving business processes and intelligence.
            It was with this mindset that I started applying my coding skills to solve real-world problems.
            <br /><br />
            For example, in the Ministry of Transport and Infrastructure, I created a solution for corrupted data entries.
            The marine engine registration system contained products from 810 manufacturers with 15,153 distinct serial number formats.
            The problem was that the serial numbers had been entered manually without any validation system.
            <br /><br />
            The General Manager requested that each engine producer provide the serial number rules to be used for validating the entries.
            I gave a presentation explaining that this is not a sustainable solution, given that the number of producers is unlimited and the format standards are not restrictive.
            There are so many engines on the market that their producers may no longer be available.
            <br /><br />
            I suggested an alternative solution. I had developed an application to analyse serial numbers and extract formats from existing data entries.
            I developed a method to identify outlier format types and proposed a solution to reduce the number of formats to an easily manageable level.
            <br /><br />
            I also offered a procedure whereby officers can easily apply for a new format registry that will be approved within a few minutes using human intervention, provided they enter a serial number that has not been identified before.
            This solution is still in use. The number of serial number formats was reduced from 15,153 to 2,433.
            <br /><br />
            Besides these, I was also deeply interested in Machine Learning and Neural Networks. 
            I started learning Python in 2019 and tinkering with a JavaScript ML library, ml5.js.
            <br /><br />
            In 2020, I started M.Sc. program in Computational Science and Engineering where I studied chaotic systems and analysis. I used Machine Learning and Applied mathematics for the analysis.
            <br /><br />
            I developed a unique technique to model Epidemic systems. I suggested a way to apply Triangular Probabilistic Dsitribution to Delay Differential Equations.
            As it was realy a unique approach, it was a challenge for me to explain my professor. When he realised that I was working on a real solution and saw the results he got amazed and supported my study with great effort.
            <br /><br />
            In 2023, I published a paper with my Advisor professor about thetechnique I developed. —Aybar, O.Ö., Şentürk, M., (2023). “Implementation of a triangular
            probabilistic distribution for optimal parameterization of the SEIR model recovery rates with delay”, Chaos: an Interdisciplinary Journal
            of Nonlinear Science, https://doi.org/10.1063/5.0164226.
            <br /><br />
            <b>2022 - Software Development</b>
            <br /><br />
            Naval Architecture, despite its name, is a field of engineering with strong foundations in physics, mathematics and materials science —focused on design and construction of marine vessels. That’s where I come from.
            <br /><br />
            I realized that software development offered a much broader platform for me to do just that.
            The dynamic nature of the field, the ability to build complex systems from the ground up, and the constant evolution of technology really attracted me.
            I saw software development as an opportunity to apply my problem-solving and design thinking skills in a more impactful way.
            So I started a new career in software development.
            <br /><br />
            I really enjoy studying Computer Science and philosophy of software development. It is amazing to witness the emergence of such impressive systems above layers of abstractions, from logic circuits to networks.
            <br /><br />
            While I value my experience in naval architecture, I'm excited to pursue my passion for software development, where I can innovate and contribute to shaping the digital world.
            <br /><br />
            I believe that the power is in our dreams, which enables us to percept and recreate the world around us.
